places.generalDescription: Olympiapark M√ºnchen is a sprawling complex that was built for the 1972 Olympic Games and has since become one of Munich's most popular attractions. The park features iconic structures such as the Olympic Stadium, Olympic Hall, and the towering Olympic Tower with its observation deck. Visitors can enjoy guided tours, concerts, and a variety of sports activities within the 850,000 square meter park.

sources.snippet: The 1972 Olympic Games were held in Munich, and many of the venues created for the event are located in what is now known as the Olympiapark. Munich is recognized globally for its success in turning the Olympic venues into spaces that continue to be used and generate income for the city. If you‚Äôre visiting Munich, you might watch a concert or attend a festival in the Olympic Stadium.

sources.snippet: While many former Olympic venues around the world tend to be forgotten, Munich‚Äôs 1972 Olympic Park is still a popular day out. The park is a massive activity centre where you can ride a zip-line over the iconic stadium, take part in watersports on the lake and ski on the hill in winter. There are also fairground amusements in summer, and no lack of places to grab a snack or meal.

A Fantastic Day at Olympiapark M√ºnchen!
Visiting Olympiapark M√ºnchen was an unforgettable experience! The park is not only beautifully maintained but also full of life and history. We truly enjoyed walking through the spacious grounds, taking in the unique architecture of the Olympic facilities and the stunning lake views.

And clearly loved by the locals for exercise and relaxation. The whole place has such a vibrant yet peaceful atmosphere, making it perfect for both sightseeing and simply enjoying nature. Highly recommended for anyone visiting Munich! üåü

Absolutely beautiful place. Very well maintained. The sea world is good but not worth the high price tag it carries. Far more beautiful aquariums exist at a much lesser price. The real attraction lies in the pond side benches behind the sea world. Tranquil, pretty and a great place to just sit by and catch your thoughts.

places.generalDescription: Marienplatz is the bustling city-center square and transportation hub in Munich, Germany. It features the towering St. Peter's church, two town halls, and a toy museum. Visitors can start their day with a hearty breakfast before joining the Free Walking Tour of Munich at Marienplatz, where knowledgeable guides lead a 2-2.5 hour tour of popular city areas.

sources.snippet: Of all the city squares, Marienplatz is Munich's most popular square. It used to be a marketplace and is still one of the most bustling parts of the city today. The first thing you will notice is the impressive Neues Rathaus (New Town Hall) and impressive architecture.
sources.shortName: Photo Guide: The Top 16 Most Instagrammable Places in Munich, Germany

sources.snippet: It was all bombed away during World War II. But the neo-gothic New Town Hall ( Neues Rathaus) on the central square makes up for it!. Here‚Äôs a detailed guide to Marienplatz. Make sure to explore the inner courtyard as well.

places.name: Marienplatz

reviews.text: Beautiful square with cafes and the old town hall with the beautiful glockenspiel clock that chimes and does a show  at 11am and 12 pm. Very busy tourist attraction, lots of different access points from lots of shopping streets.

Excellent. Lots of people. LOTS of people. But it was super cute. It's hard to believe it's all less than 100 years old! They did an excellent job rebuilding. Excellent. We had a lovely afternoon strolling. And then as we were leaving we happened upon Ralph Kiefer, an incredibly talented musician playing outside the church. St Peter's I think. (It's tough because we couldn't see signs/names of the churches so we weren't sure‚Ä¶)

Beautiful plaza, very historic‚Ä¶ for better or worse. Site of the famous Munich Farmers Market before it was moved nearby. The old and now town halls still present. The start of good shopping and restaurants. Lookup the glockenspiel operation times so you can hear the bells and watch the show.

places.generalDescription: Allianz Arena, home to Bayern Munich, is a renowned football stadium and one of the most impressive athletic venues globally. Designed by Herzog & de Meuron, its unique architecture features 2,784 ETFE plastic panels that give it a distinctive appearance resembling an inflatable cushion with translucent air pockets. What sets it apart is its luminous exterior that changes color based on the team playing: red for Bayern, blue for TSV 1860, and white for Germany.

sources.snippet: Sports fans who‚Äôve ever wondered if football (soccer) is popular in Munich need only visit Allianz Arena Stadium, which seats more than 75,000 spectators who want to see one of the city‚Äôs two teams take the field. The stadium replaced the city‚Äôs Olympic stadium beginning with the 2005-2006 season. The stadium, which hosted the World Cup finals in 2006, is known for its panels that change colors, depending on which team is playing and the type of match, i.e., local or national, being played.

sources.snippet: Even if you only have a passing interest in football, a visit to the home of FC Bayern has to be on the agenda. That‚Äôs not just because they‚Äôre Germany‚Äôs top team and have a special place in the nation‚Äôs culture, but they also moved into an awesome new home just over a decade ago. The 66,000-seater stadium is clad with 2,874 luminous panels, which light up with the club‚Äôs colours on match-days.

places.generalDescription: Viktualienmarkt is a lively and vibrant 200-year-old farmers' market in Munich, offering a wide variety of regional culinary delights. With over 100 stalls selling everything from fresh produce to artisanal cheeses and meats, it's a paradise for food lovers and anyone interested in experiencing Bavarian flavors. Families can enjoy the diverse array of food options and the open-air ambiance.

sources.snippet: A post shared by Marina Trushina (@kteshka) on Mar 22, 2018 at 12:41am PDT. It‚Äôs just too classically Munich to pass up: in the center of the wonderful Viktualienmarkt‚ÄîMunich‚Äôs excellent year-round open-air farmer‚Äôs market‚Äîis a large Maibaum, or Maypole, a common sight around Bavaria; but this Maypole is particularly large and attractive and is the perfect meeting point in the center of town. (By the way, traditionally Maypoles can be stolen by rival towns, and the successful thieves must have a party thrown for them in order to get their Maypole back.) Grab a fresh juice or cup of coffee from one of the nearby stands, or perhaps a wurst or a giant pickle, get in front of the Maypole (if it hasn‚Äôt been stolen!) and strike a pose.

But that is only half the story, as there‚Äôs a big biergarten in the centre of the marketplace, and one of Munich‚Äôs favourites.

reviews.text: A great local market showcasing German foods, fruits and vegetables, cheeses, souvenirs and more. The beer garden in the center is nice to sit and we appreciated that there were free bathrooms. It wasn't too crowded on a weekday morning, so we got to look at all the vendors and take our time.

Incredible outdoor market‚Ä¶ over 200 years and going strong. There are flower, fruit and vegetable vendors, along with prepared food and drink stalls. There's also a Biergarten. Closed Sunday. 8a to 8P during summer.
Loved all the little outdoor stands packed with fresh fruits, veggies, and food stalls. Plenty of spots to sit outside too. The sausage I had was so good!

places.generalDescription: Eisbachwelle is a unique and popular attraction in Munich's Englischer Garten, drawing surf enthusiasts and spectators from around the world for over 40 years. This continuous wave on the Eisbach River offers year-round surfing opportunities and is one of the most constant and largest river waves in a major city. Located near the Haus der Kunst, it has become a hotspot for both admirers of surfers' skills and those who want to ride the wave themselves.

Interesting spot. It is open and good to see surfers out there honing their skills. It's no comparison to the Great Barrier Reef in Sydney but it's a good start to get at it.

places.generalDescription: The English Garden, located in Munich, is an expansive 18th-century urban park that boasts 78 kilometers of cycling and jogging trails. Larger than Central Park, it offers a pastoral escape within the city. The park features a lakeside beer garden and provides various leisure activities such as biking, jogging, and recreational games like football. Additionally, the neighborhood surrounding the English Garden is home to seven academic centers and compact museum areas, making it a favorite among locals, students, and visitors.

sources.snippet: Hang out with the locals and get some epic shots of your Munich getaway in English Garden. Enjoy a leisurely stroll through the park or rent a bike to see more on your exploration of this popular tranquil space in Munich. Between the volleyball courts, groups of friends having picnics, and the little buildings and landmarks scattered around, there's always something going on. It's a great spot to hang out, and the sunset over the park is a perfect way to end the day.
This is a very beautiful garden. It is very large and it is relaxing. I highly recommend it to anyone who visits Munich. The river surfing was incredible.

A kind of ‚ÄúCentral Park‚Äù in Munich ‚Äì a very nice place to visit. The park is spacious, green, and perfect for a walk or to just relax. A special highlight is the surfers on the river ‚Äì definitely a must-see attraction that makes this place unique.

places.generalDescription: Nymphenburg Palace is a grand 200-hectare estate showcasing stunning rococo interiors, an impressive coach display, and symmetrical baroque gardens. The palace offers a peek into Bavaria's royal history with its opulent halls and the renowned Gallery of Beauties. It appeals to history buffs, art enthusiasts, and admirers of grand architecture. Visitors can explore the meticulously manicured gardens and discover charming pavilions like the enchanting rococo follies.

reviews.text: The palace was‚Ä¶mid the main hall is excellent, but there were little rooms opened to the public, considering how enormous the palace is. But the park is where it shined, one of the best royal parks I have seen, there were lakes European gardens, Chinese pavilions, Long canals, and the weather was perfect. There were also two other museums that are amazing, one should book the combined ticket when going.

The Palace is from the age of opulence. Visually stunning rooms, as well as understanding an age of absolute rule.

There is something for everyone. Architecture,  horses, art, pottery and porcelain,  trees and gardens, history.

There are extensive grounds so its worth walking to the outer palaces. The walk under the trees is relaxing even on a warm day.

Expect to spend a good few hours there.

Note. You need to leave your bags in lockers while touring the main palace.

We've visited this palace in both winter and summer. In winter, it's much quieter, making it easy to explore and appreciate the palace's details, though the gardens are bare. In summer, however, the gardens come alive in full bloom. My favorite part of the visit is strolling through the garden, enjoying the breeze, and finding relief from the heat in the shade.

places.generalDescription: Located in Munich, the Hofbr√§uhaus M√ºnchen is a historic 3-floor beer hall and Bavarian restaurant that dates back to 1589. It offers an authentic taste of Bavarian culture with its lively atmosphere, traditional music, and classic Bavarian dishes. This iconic beer hall appeals to beer enthusiasts, food connoisseurs, and travelers seeking an immersive experience in Bavarian hospitality. Visitors are encouraged to arrive early to secure seating and can enjoy extended hours of operation.

sources.snippet: If you‚Äôre up for a beer, a carefree atmosphere and helping of traditional Bavarian fare a beer hall or Wirtshaus would be just the ticket. There are dozens to choose from around Munich and with a little research you‚Äôll find an authentic one near you. And even though you won‚Äôt find many locals in the Hofbr√§uhaus, it‚Äôs still one of those things you have to do in Munich.

sources.snippet: Munich residents do love their beer, celebrating it annually at Oktoberfest. Travelers who won‚Äôt be here then can still sip the suds at the Hofbrauhaus, one of the oldest breweries in town. The Hofbrauhaus dates back to 1589 when it was founded by Wilhelm V, Duke of Bavaria, when it served as the official brewery for Munich‚Äôs royalty.

reviews.text: Loved the busy atmosphere,  the hustle of the staff members, the lively conversations, and the smiles of everyone around!  The food was okay and the beer was good..  Of course, there are only two choices of beer, and they generally come in large quantity, so it's hard to be wrong with that!

Honestly worth going as a traveller. It has live music, bustling atmosphere and great character. It is touristy, but worth going to check out at least once. We sat in the main ground level grab-your-own seating area near the back, no need to wait - just find a spot and sit.

We grabbed the standard pork knuckle with dumpling and beer, enjoyed some music, and mix of visitors. The food was a bit salty but reasonable with beer, and it was more for the communal festive atmosphere. We were here just before Oktoberfest, so the surrounding shops were already ramping up to it, and everyone was lively.

We had the house sausage plate and the potato salad and their beer which was amazing all of it. Great music great atmosphere good times. Delicious food. The sauerkraut was just lightly sweet and quite amazing. Everything tasted fresh clean. So not gross like most American food back home.

places.generalDescription: BMW Welt is a futuristic distribution center and exhibition hall located near the Olympiastadion in Munich. It serves as a vast showroom where visitors can admire the entire current product offering of BMW, including sedans, Minis, racing cars, electric vehicles, and even Rolls-Royces. The building itself is an architectural wonder made of glass and steel twisted into a double cone with a roof resembling a floating cloud.

sources.snippet: After learning about BMW‚Äôs past you can be brought up to date with the present at the stylish exhibition hall next door. BMW Welt is free to enter and the best explanation is that it‚Äôs the world‚Äôs most spectacular car dealership showroom. People come to pick up their new BMWs, which is a spectacle in its own right as their car is lifted up to them by elevator into a glass hall.
sources.shortName: 25 Best Things to Do in Munich (Germany)

sources.snippet: BMW is known for its fast cars and motorcycles; what better place to learn more about them than BMW Welt and the BMW museum. BMW Welt is a place to see and gain knowledge of the company‚Äôs latest product offerings. BMW Welt also sells auxiliary accessories and parts for their vehicles, and hosts exhibitions of their latest models.

sources.snippet: Many of them are produced in Bavaria and BMW even has its headquarters in the city. There is also the fabulous BMW World (basically a permanent car show) and the BMW museum. Together, they form a beautiful ensemble that rightfully belongs on any list of the best photography spots in Munich.

places.name: BMW Welt

reviews.text: We visited BMW Welt this past week when we were in Munich. It is free to enter and explore. What an amazing experience. It is free to enter. It serves as a multifunctional exhibition, delivery, and event center. It is located across the street from the BMW HQ and Museum and next to the Olympic Park in Munich. To me it is a prime example of customer Experience. We watched people drive off in their new BMW. What a tremendous feeling. There are plenty of car exhibits from BMW, Mini, Motorcycles, Rolls Royce. There is a huge BMW shop and plenty of places to get something to eat. BMW really does it right with BMW Welt. Never seen anything like it in my life. Just spectacular. We loved our visit.

Impressive place to visit whilst in Munich even if you don't like cars. The building itself is impressive and it's right opposite the Olympic park which is a nice place to walk around.

We even went back to BMW Welt in the evening to see it lit up and we're surprised to find it open until midnight so we almost had the place to ourselves!

Maybe one day I'll be back collecting a BMW of my own!

An unforgettable experience! I have been driving a BMW for 8 years, but visiting the BMW Museum was truly something special. I felt an incredible emotion seeing the brand's history and discovering the latest models. I highly recommend it to every car enthusiast!

places.generalDescription: Hellabrunn Zoo, located on the banks of the river Isar, is a nature reserve-style zoo that houses over 750 species from around the world. The zoo covers 89 acres and was the first to group animals based on their place of origin. With more than 1,900 animals living in large open spaces that replicate their native habitats, Hellabrunn Zoo provides a humane environment for its inhabitants.

sources.snippet: In 40 hectares on the meadow-covered right bank of the Isar in the south of the city, Hellabrunn Zoo rarely ranks outside the top five in Europe. Established in 1911, it was one of the first in world to adopt moats and ditches as barriers instead of cages, but also introduced the concept of the Geo-Zoo, where animals are located according to their geographical regions. If you‚Äôre concerned about the zoo‚Äôs humane credentials, it takes part in breeding programs for endangered species like silvery and drill baboons, as well as elephants, Arctic foxes and gorillas.
sources.shortName: 25 Best Things to Do in Munich (Germany)

places.name: Hellabrunn Zoo

reviews.text: One of the most beautiful zoos I've ever visited. Plenty of trees and shades. Variety of animals grouping together while it is quite close and open to see them. They have pretty good restaurants with quality food. Also have a few playgrounds that are super nice! I came here during summer time and it is perfect weather.
Absolutely amazing! The park is really big and has so many different animals, all in large and very well-kept spaces. It's perfect for kids-my son had so much fun and we really enjoyed the day.

Absolutely must go if you have more than 3 days in Munich! One of the best zoos in terms of animal husbandry. Most of the exhibits were massive allowing a lot of room for the animals to roam. Most animals were lively and playful. The Biergarten was a plus and a delicious break from the hike.

places.generalDescription: Frauenkirche, also known as the Church of Our Lady, is a restored Gothic church in Munich with two towers that top its structure. The church is famous for its legendary Devil's footprint, which has several variations of the story behind it. One version tells how the Prince of Hell helped the architect build the church and was to collect his soul as a reward after completion. However, the clever master builder outwitted the devil.

sources.snippet: Frauenkirche, or the Church of Our Lady, is one M√ºnchen Instagram spot that you won‚Äôt want to miss out on. It‚Äôs definitely one of the more popular places to visit, even though it‚Äôs located only a short walk from Rathaus, Marienplatz, and St. Peter‚Äôs Church. The church was built in the 15th century but, of course, had more construction and restoration since then.
sources.shortName: M√ºnchen Instagram Spots: 16 Most Instagrammable Places in Munich, Germany

sources.snippet: The Munich Frauenkirche is another famous Munich landmark that towers over the rest of the city. It dates back to the 15th century when it was built in an astounding 20 years‚Äô time, though completion of some features was postponed due to lack of money. The Munich Frauenkirche serves as the cathedral for the Archdiocese of Munich and is home to the archbishop.

Its pair of towers, crowned with onion domes are a Munich landmark, and no new building is permitted to exceed their 109-metre height. The church‚Äôs design is famously discreet, with few window openings and unadorned walls that inspire awe.

reviews.text:
A beautiful church with outstanding architecture and interesting history covered with legends.
We visited the viewpoint in the south tower in May 2024 and the views were breathtaking. I especially liked the views of the north tower, it looked so close to the windows!
The interactive maps are very helpful and fun to use. They show the same view you see from the windows, and you can tap on any building and read about it.
The 3D postcards are pricey but extremely beautiful.

Beautiful church with interesting legend about its construction.  Beautiful inside and out. Nice place to find a quiet place to sit and rest in the middle of hectic historical center of Munich. One can spend 5 or 25 minutes here.

Frauenkirche is impossible to miss; the twin onion-domed towers are basically the city's calling card, looming above the skyline since their completion in 1488. Up close, the Late Gothic brickwork feels fortress-like, but step inside and it shifts: the soaring white interior, with its slender columns and ribbed vaults, feels almost weightless. Light filters through stained glass that miraculously survived the bombing of World War II, giving the space a quiet dignity.

What surprised me most, though, wasn't the grandeur but the details: the ‚ÄúDevil's Footprint‚Äù in the floor, linked to a centuries-old legend, and the striking tomb of Emperor Ludwig IV (who died in 1347), guarded by bronze knights. It's these little touches that make the cathedral more than just an architectural icon, it's a place layered with stories, power, and myth. Standing there, you feel both the scale of Bavarian history and the human quirks that keep it alive.

places.generalDescription: K√∂nigsplatz is a historic square in Munich, featuring grand neo-classical buildings such as the Propylaen gateway and two temple-like museums. Originally designed by Leo von Klenze and later expanded by the Nazis, the square now offers a peaceful and green space for visitors to enjoy concerts and open-air cinema during the summer. Flanked by neoclassical structures housing Munich's antiquities, K√∂nigsplatz also serves as a starting point for walking tours through the city.

sources.snippet: The K√∂nigsplatz is a public square built in the 19th century. The square holds deep historical significance for Germany - the building once served as a representative building for Adolf Hitler and the square is where Hitler held many of his rallies and ceremonies. To learn more about the historical significance of this place, sign up for one of the many walking tours here.

K√∂nigsplatz in Munich is a beautiful and peaceful square, known for its impressive neoclassical architecture and open space. Surrounded by grand buildings like the Glyptothek and the Staatliche Antikensammlungen, it has a majestic yet relaxing atmosphere, making it a great place to take a break from the city's busy streets.

During lunchtime, the square comes to life with people sitting on the steps or grass, enjoying their meals in the fresh air. The combination of history, architecture, and a laid-back vibe makes it a perfect spot to soak in the beauty of Munich-whether you're exploring the museums or just looking for a quiet place to relax.

‚≠ê K√∂nigsplatz, Munich
A breathtaking neoclassical forum rooted in Bavarian Romanticism - glimmering Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian facades inspired by ancient Athens. The towering Propyl√§en leads into a square flanked by the Glyptothek and the Staatliche Antikensammlungen, all echoing King Ludwig I's vision of an ‚ÄúIsar-Athens.‚Äù A place rich with historical layers-from art and architecture to Nazi propaganda and modern cultural resurgence. Today, it hosts concerts and quiet moments alike and sits proudly at the heart of Munich's museum district. Easily reached via U-Bahn (U2/U8). #Munich #Konigsplatz #Neoclassical #CulturalLandmark

places.generalDescription: The BMW Museum in Munich is a futuristic steel structure that showcases engines, designs, and vintage as well as new cars from the renowned brand. It offers a diverse array of exhibits that cater to various interests, making it an ideal stop for anyone visiting Munich. The museum provides an immersive journey through the development of the automotive industry, featuring exceptional presentations of exhibits that trace its evolution from its earliest beginnings to modern times.

sources.snippet: Karl Schwanzer, the man who designed the famous BMW Headquarters also drew up the plans for the futuristic museum building in front, often described as the ‚Äúsalad bowl‚Äù. The building was completed in 1973 and its galleries are on a Guggenheim-esque spiral. The showrooms are air, spacious and effortlessly cool, as you go on a journey through the brand‚Äôs technological development.

reviews.text:
We had a fantastic visit to the BMW Museum. We'd booked the guided tour in advance, which started promptly with a lovely tour guide who was friendly, engaging, and brilliant with our children (age 9). The tour lasted just over an hour and covered the majority of the museum, with plenty of fascinating facts about the exhibits. I highly recommend booking the tour ‚Äì you get fast-track access, headsets for clear audio throughout, and the chance to see under the bonnet of some of the cars.

On arrival, remember to store your belongings in the lockers downstairs. We had a quick stop in the museum caf√© ‚Äì the selection was fine but limited ‚Äì and a browse through the small gift shop. Overall, it was a great experience for the whole family.

Recently visited the BMW Museum during our stay in Munich. Located next to headquarters and the BMW Welt. An amazing experience and fascinating journey through the company history, innovation, and design evolvement of this world famous German car brand. The excellent and well structured exhibitions display history and chronological development from the earliest BMW models and motorcycles to the latest concept cars and technology.
Very educational and encompassing interactive displays, historical documents, and multimedia installations. Not only for BMW owners and fans, suitable for anyone interested in automotive history, innovation, and German engineering. Highly recommended!

My first trip to Europe had me spending a day in Munich. I didn't realize it was the home of the BMW Museum, until after I arrived. I own and frequently ride a BMW touring motorcycle and had heard great things about the museum from a friend.  It did not disappoint!  I learned about the history of the company‚Ä¶of which I only knew a fraction.  Cars, motorcycles, boats, and aircraft were all on display.

A lot of thought went into the design and the tour was quite pleasant.  We opted for the self-guided tour at our own pace.  They also offer a guided tour in English as well.  Those on the guided tour were treated to additional insights‚Ä¶I lingered just long enough to capture a few glimpses.

They've got a cafe with tasty drinks and treats too.

Overall, a good value for the price and definitely worth the time‚Ä¶about 2.5 hours inside.

reviews.text:
Munich is a masterpiece of authentic architecture.
Once you step into the downtown area, all you need to do is walk-every corner unveils a different era, a unique style, a story carved in stone. Wander freely, let the city guide you. Step into charming old buildings, grand halls, and cozy hidden gems. And whatever you do, don't miss St. Peter's Church. It's a striking symbol of German craftsmanship, where towering statues and intricate details leave a lasting impression.

St Peter is an impressive Catholic church in the center of Old Town. The building is usually open daily to tourists. They also have an observation deck at the top of the bell tower. The church is free to enter, and tower admission was only ‚Ç¨5 when I visited. Tower tickets can be purchased at the base of the tower as walk-up only (no reservations accepted unless you want a night tour).

Keep in mind there are 306 steps to the top of the tower, but the view is worth the climb. On your way up, you can see the massive bells. At the top, you get wonderful views of Marienplatz and all of Old Town. The church nave itself features ornate decoration with accents of pink and gold on white, making it a peaceful space of reflection. I highly recommend this for anyone interested in architecture, history, or great city views.

Stunning church in Munich. It is free to enter but costs to climb the tower. St. Peter is the oldest parish church in Munich. It dates back to the 8th to 12th century. It was originally built as a Romanesque church and later rebuilt in Gothic style. The architecture is just stunning as well as all the decoration inside the church. The high altar and sculptures are beautiful. The church has eight bells and four of them pre-date 1400. This is a must visit in Munich! We loved our visit.

places.generalDescription: Located in the Munich suburbs, Schleissheim Palace complex is a stunning ensemble of three palaces that served as the summer residence for Bavarian Royals. The palace displays religious folk art and hosts exhibits on Prussian art and culture. Despite being an underrated destination, it boasts beautiful architecture and a huge park, making it a great spot for photography. While many tourists flock to well-known castles in Munich, Schleissheim Palace remains a hidden gem waiting to be explored.

Not a bad visit. Not too expensive if you don't pay for the guided tours. Lots of walking. We enjoyed the autumn foliage. Prob would have been fine without paying and just walking around. Nice way to kill a 7 hr layover at Munich airport.

Schlei√üheim palace complex was founded by Duke Wilhelm V of Bavaria (1548-1626), who in 1597 purchased the isolated moorland farm of Schlei√üheim with its St Margaret's Chapel for a large sum of money from the Freising Cathedral chapter. Wilhelm renounced the splendours of court life at an early stage, devoted himself to religious meditation and in 1598 finally abdicated in favour of his energetic son Maximilian. The founding of Schlei√üheim reflected his personal inclination towards pious contemplation.

In the period from 1598 to 1600 Wilhelm had an estate and a manor built within the complex, which was surrounded by small hermitages and forest chapels. The duke, who had no intention of altering the character of the property as a farm, extended its activities with a stud farm which supplied his stables. Schlei√üheim beer and Schlei√üheim cheese were produced. Attracted in particular by the profits from the farming business, Maximilian I (reigned 1598-1651) acquired the complex from his father in 1616 in return for a life annuity The Schlei√üheim park was designed in strict alignment with Lustheim and the New Palace and is one of the most important baroque gardens in Europe.

It was initially influenced by Dutch garden design, and subsequently extended by the French garden expert and waterworks engineer Dominique Gerard in the French baroque garden style. With his embroidered parterres, pools, fountains and cascades he created a unique design, the basic features of which have remained unchanged.

The ensemble consisting of the New and Old Palaces, Lustheim Palace and the extensive baroque garden is a splendid example of court architecture and garden design from the 17th and 18th centuries.

places.generalDescription: The Botanical Garden Munich-Nymphenburg is a sprawling 52-acre complex that features a diverse range of themed gardens, greenhouses, and ponds inhabited by turtles. Visitors can also enjoy the amenities of a cafe and gift shop on the premises. Established in 1914, this botanical garden and arboretum is home to an impressive collection of over 19,000 plant species and subspecies. The garden serves as a vital sanctuary for rare plants and European bee species.

sources.snippet: The Botanischer Garten M√ºnchen is one of my personal favorite spots in Munich. I especially love it in early spring when all the spring flowers are blooming but the big greenhouses will be beautiful even in winter. There are also greenhouses, which host a variety of artificial climates from all around the world, and some turtles too in the orchid room! After a stressful week at a work conference it was great to come here and relax. Highly recommend visiting the gardens if you're in Munich, it's inexpensive too. The cafe is also lovely!

What a great place to spend an afternoon. A lush botanical garden with all sorts of plants, flowers and plant loving critters. While the rose garden wasn't a main attraction, the greenhouse enclosures were very expansive. Cacti and orchid areas were quite fascinating. The lotus pond was straight out of a painting. Well worth the entry fee!

Stunning place. The variety of plants and flowers is impressive, and for ‚Ç¨5.5 for a standard adult ticket this is definitely a steal. The greenhouses are fantastic - packed with all sorts of tropical plants! The only thing I would change is writing more plant descriptions in English. Still, wholeheartedly recommended!

places.generalDescription: The Residenz Museum, a former royal palace in Munich, is a must-visit for culture lovers. It was the residence and seat of government of the Wittelsbach dynasty who ruled Bavaria. The museum showcases original interiors and royal collections, offering visitors a glimpse into the opulent lifestyle of the royals. While there is an admission fee to enter, it's worth it for history and art enthusiasts.

places.name: Residenz Museum

reviews.text:
The Residenz Museum in Munich is a breathtaking palace and one of the most impressive historical sites in the city. Located just a short walk from Marienplatz in the heart of the Old Town, it's incredibly convenient to visit while exploring Munich's central attractions.

Inside, the museum is absolutely stunning. Each room is beautifully decorated, from grand gilded halls to intricate frescoed ceilings and lavishly furnished chambers. The sheer variety of styles and designs makes every step through the palace a visual delight.

However, the Residenz is huge-with countless rooms, long corridors, and hidden corners, it's easy to lose yourself in its magnificence. But getting a little lost only adds to the charm, as there's always another breathtaking space waiting to be discovered.

The Munich Residence is beautifully restored  to showcase the history and art collections of the German ruling class. Since much of the palace was destroyed during WWII, many of the rooms have been fully recreated and much of the original furniture and art has been lost. The main route through the building is well marked and there is a split in the middle where you have the option of a shorter tour skipping some of the rooms. Only a few of the rooms were really crowded, since the building is so large the crowd is dispersed nicely so you get to move through almost by yourself. There is an audio guide available, but I forgot to get one and still spent 2.5 hours on my visit. They have a coat and bag check area for free.

The Munich Residenz is stunning - We visited here with my family and my kids absolutely loved it.  You will find centuries of art, power, and excellence.

It's a lot to take in, so give yourself at least 2 hours.

Highly recommend if you're in Munich and want a break from beer gardens (or just need to feel fancy for a bit).

places.generalDescription: Siegestor, a 19th-century triumphal arch in Munich, is reminiscent of the Brandenburg Gate and was commissioned by King Ludwig as a tribute to victory. Resembling the Arch of Constantine, it suffered significant damage during World War II but has been partially restored over a 30-year period. The arch features a bronze sculpture of Bavaria with four lions and stands at the north end of Ludwigstrasse.

sources.snippet: Siegestor in M√ºnchen is a triumphal arch situated at the terminus of the Ludwigstra√üe built to commemorate the bravery of the Bavarian army and its success in the Napoleonic War of liberation. One of the main Landmarks of Leopoldstra√üe. Translated as Victory gate,  was completed in 1857, the inscription on the back side is by Wilhelm

A little disappointed. Too many art pieces on display. Not keen on audio tours. Probably would have gotten more from the audio tour. Nice grounds to walk around. They have set times for the palace tour to keep the crowd limited. Makes for a better visit.

Leopoldstrasse and Ludwigstrasse are turned into a massive pedestrian zone twice a year. A colourful festival mile pulls tens of thousands of people to Schwabing and Maxvorstadt, where cars regularly drive through the city.

Two weekends a year, Leopoldstrasse and Ludwigstrasse are turned into an adventure mile. One of the biggest of its sort in Europe, the street festival is held once in the spring and once in the autumn. In actuality, though, these are two street celebrations that started apart from one another and originally prioritised idealism over partying.

Perched atop a 49-foot hill, this Grecian-style bandstand offers stunning views of central Munich and its iconic landmarks. While the garden is known for activities like river surfing and sunbathing, the Monopteros provides a serene spot to watch the sunset over Munich's skyline.

A small classical Greek-style gazebo without walls looks out on a popular section of the park in the Schwabing district; in the summer, you may even see some folks practicing Freikorperkultur‚Äîotherwise known as naked sunbathing.

The iconic Glockenspiel housed within the town hall comes to life daily with moving figurines and chimes, adding to the vibrant atmosphere of Marienplatz.

places.name: New Town Hall

reviews.text:
Exceptionally beautiful Gothic style building in the heart of Munich.
Every year in May they open up to visitors (or you can go on a guided tour). Highly recommend as the inside is fantastic. Stained glass throughout, beautiful library, and fun architecture all around.

City Hall (Rathaus) is an impressive neo-gothic building in the heart of Old Town. The facade is most famous for the glockenspiel, which sings and dances every day at 11:00 and 12:00 (and 17:00 in the summer). The inner courtyard is open to the public and features a restaurant and public restrooms. Guided tours of the inside are available. I was allowed to free roam inside, but I think that might only happen in May. There is also an observation deck at the top of the tower. The interior is an intriguing maze of stairs, corridors, and stained glass. The inside is worth a visit for the architecture alone.

Munich's New Town Hall dominates Marienplatz with its dramatic neo-Gothic fa√ßade, soaring tower, and wealth of detail that makes you want to stare up until your neck protests. Built between 1867 and 1909 by architect Georg von Hauberrisser, it replaced the cramped Old Town Hall and quickly became the city's political and symbolic heart. The 85-meter tower is home to the famous Glockenspiel, which still draws crowds daily to watch figures reenact 16th-century Bavarian stories.

The exterior is packed with statues, floral balconies, and spires that look medieval but are purely 19th-century romanticism. Inside, the building still houses the city government, but visitors can ride the elevator up the tower for sweeping views across Munich.

During WWII, much of the city center was destroyed, yet the Neues Rathaus was repaired and restored, preserving its role as a backdrop for everything from Christmas markets to championship celebrations for FC Bayern.

places.generalDescription: The Theatine Church, also known as the Church of St. Cajetan, is a stunning Catholic church located on Odeon Square in Munich. Its striking yellow facade and ornate white stucco interior make it a must-see for visitors to the city. Construction began in 1663 to celebrate the birth of Maximilien-Emmanuel, future monarch, and was completed in 1690 with the addition of the Elector's family tomb and two towers.

places.name: Theatine Church

reviews.text:
LThe Theatine Church (Theatinerkirche) is one of Munich's most beautiful and distinctive churches, instantly recognizable by its striking yellow fa√ßade and ornate Baroque design. Located on Odeonsplatz, it adds a touch of Italian elegance to the city's architecture.

Inside, the church contrasts its bright exterior with a stunning all-white interior filled with intricate stucco work, soaring columns, and a beautifully detailed high altar. The atmosphere is peaceful and awe-inspiring, making it a great place for quiet reflection amid the bustling city.

As the final resting place of several Bavarian royals, the church also has historical significance. Whether you're drawn by its art, history, or simply its beauty, the Theatine Church is well worth a visit when exploring Munich!

A radiant gem of Baroque elegance at Odeonsplatz! Its mustard-yellow Rococo fa√ßade, twin towers, and majestic dome (71 m) bring Italian grandeur to the heart of Munich. Inside, pure white stucco, dramatic columns, and a luminous dome create a serene counterpoint. Explore the regal crypt holding 47 Wittelsbach rulers, including Max Emanuel. places.name: Pinakothek der Moderne

reviews.text:
The Pinakothek der Moderne in Munich is a fantastic museum that offers a wide-ranging collection of modern and contemporary art. The museum is spacious, with several floors dedicated to different artistic movements, making it a real treat for art lovers. Its size is one of its biggest strengths, as it gives you plenty of room to explore and immerse yourself in the vast collection without feeling crowded. You can easily spend hours here, moving through diverse galleries that showcase everything from 20th-century classics to cutting-edge contemporary works.

The collection itself is truly interesting and diverse, featuring iconic pieces in painting, sculpture, design, and architecture. Works by artists like Picasso, Kandinsky, and Dal√≠, as well as more recent avant-garde pieces, are just the tip of the iceberg. Whether you're a fan of modernist abstraction or experimental art, there's something to captivate every visitor.

One of the standout features of the museum is its caf√©, which is the perfect place to take a break. Offering a peaceful and stylish environment, it's a great spot to relax, grab a coffee, and reflect on the art you've seen. The caf√© has a welcoming vibe and is a nice contrast to the bustling energy of the galleries.

Overall, Pinakothek der Moderne is a must-visit for anyone interested in modern art. The large size and variety of works ensure that there's something for everyone, and the well-curated exhibits make it a rewarding experience. With its beautiful design and comfortable caf√©, it's a place where you can spend hours enjoying both art and a relaxed atmosphere.

Really great museum in Munich, and it was an enjoyable experience. The museum was expansive, featuring a diverse range of fascinating displays that catered to various interests. Depending on your preferences, there was something to captivate everyone.

The museum's size means that it takes several hours to explore fully, but it is definitely worth the time. I particularly enjoyed the bottom floor, which showcased a captivating mix of modern and antique furniture designs. Meanwhile, the upper floors offered an array of art displays that were equally delightful.

The venue itself is picturesque, with the building's architecture adding to the overall experience. This museum in Munich is a must-visit for anyone in the area.

Moreover, the entry fee is quite reasonable. At just ‚Ç¨12, visitors gain access to all three museums in the vicinity, making it an excellent value for money.

Overall, I would highly recommend this museum to anyone.

If you are interested in contemporary art, you should definitely visit this museum. I came here mainly for the Paula Scher exhibition, and it was amazing to see her works in person. The museum itself is quite large, with many fascinating exhibitions covering almost every direction in art. A wonderful experience!
